1.Difference Between while and do-while Loop (3 Marks)

	while loop checks condition before execution, whereas do-while loop checks condition after execution.
	while loop may execute zero times, whereas do-while loop executes at least once.
	while loop is entry-controlled loop, whereas do-while loop is exit-controlled loop.

2️.Difference Between return and System.exit() (5 Marks)

	return statement exits from the current method, whereas System.exit() terminates the entire program.
	return transfers control back to the calling method, whereas System.exit() stops JVM execution completely.
	return can return a value (if method has return type), whereas System.exit() does not return value; it ends program.
	return is used inside methods, whereas System.exit() can be used anywhere in program.
	return does not stop finally block execution, whereas System.exit() may not execute finally block.

3️.What are Checked and Unchecked Exceptions? (6 Marks)
	Checked Exceptions:
	- Checked at compile time.
	- Must be handled using try-catch or throws.
	- Example: IOException, SQLException.
	
	Unchecked Exceptions:
	- Occur at runtime.
	- Not checked at compile time.
	- Handling is optional.
	- Example: ArithmeticException, NullPointerException.
	

4️.Difference Between throw and throws (6 Marks)
	- throw is used to explicitly throw an exception, whereas throws is used to declare exceptions.
	- throw is used inside method body, whereas throws is used in method signature.
	- throw is followed by an exception object, whereas throws is followed by exception class names.
	-throw can throw only one exception at a time, whereas throws can declare multiple exceptions.
	- throw transfers control to catch block, whereas throws passes responsibility to caller method.

5.What is a Custom Exception? (Interview Ready)

	- A custom exception is a user-defined exception created by extending the Exception class.
	- It is used to handle application-specific errors.
	
	Example:
	class InvalidAgeException extends Exception {
	    InvalidAgeException(String message) {
	        super(message);
	    }
	}